Known among Erkynlanders by the honorific Lady, a Sitha and one of the youngest of the immortal Sithi people, born after the fall of Asu'a. She is the daughter of Shima'onari and Likimeya and the sister of Jiriki. Slender in build, she is recognisable by her golden skin, golden cat-like eyes, and lavender-dyed hair. In character she is warm, curious, and openly fond of children — and notably unbothered by the conventions around clothing that humans observe. She counts Simon among her close friends, and is on familiar terms with the scholar Tanahaya.A river flowing within the Aldheorte forest. It runs parallel to the inlet stream from Geloë's lake and passes through the Sithi city of Da'ai Chikiza. Its Erkynlandish name means "Sithi River," while its Sithi name, Ts'i Suhyasei, is translated by Binabik as "Her Blood is Cool."The great forest covering much of central Osten Ard. Its name means "Old heart," and it contains ancient Sithi places such as Da'ai Chikiza as well as hidden waters, wild paths, and deep regions beyond ordinary settlement.Known as First Grandmother among the Sithi and as Amerasu Ship-Born, one of the most revered of the immortal Sithi people — an ancient wise-woman of exceptional standing. To some mortals she is known as the Lady of the Wood or Queen of Fairies. She reigned in the great Sithi city of Asu'a beside her husband Iyu'unigato, and after its fall helped lead her people to the hidden refuge of Jao é-Tinukai'i, of which she became mistress. In her long stewardship of that realm she received mortal visitors on rare occasion. In bearing she is slender and regal, with a high noble brow, startlingly golden eyes, white uncolored hair, and an amber translucence to her skin. Her manner is wise, stern, and touched with mild sarcasm.A Sitha and one of Jiriki's most trusted companions, serving as his lieutenant and hunting partner. He has black hair that shines with a green hue, and amber eyes.A Nabbanai nobleman, Count of Eadne and master of Prevan House, later elevated to the rank of Earl. A close friend of Benigaris, he moves in the highest circles of Nabbani power and serves as paymaster of the Fire Dancers. His manner is outwardly charming, though beneath the courtly surface he is entitled, ambitious, and cruel.One of the Sithi Nine Cities and, after Tumet'ai was lost, the first and greatest city of the Sithi. When occupied, it was renowned for beauty, with flowering meadows to the north and many lakes in the surrounding land. The city stands at the heart of the oldest Sithi presence in Osten Ard.A Nabbanai nobleman of the powerful Benidrivine house, heir to the Duchy of Nabban. Tall and broad-shouldered, with intense dark eyes beneath thick black brows — a more imposing figure than his father Leobardis, though slightly heavy about the waist. He is the son of Leobardis and Nessalanta, cousin of Miriamele on his mother's side, and brother of Varellan and Antippa.A Qanuc troll from the mountain of Mintahoq, and the apprentice of Ookequk, the Singing Man of the Qanuc and a member of the ancient League of the Scroll. Orphaned early in life when his parents were killed in a dragon-snow accident, Binabik devoted himself to his studies under Ookequk, travelling far across Osten Ard and becoming well versed in its many cultures, histories, and languages — among them Qanuc, Sithi, and Erkynlandish. He is betrothed to Sisqinanamook. Compact even by the diminutive standards of the Troll folk, he has a round, childlike face with narrow eyes and a wide mouth, and black hair. In character he is kind, intelligent, and possessed of a strong sense of honour; measured and level-headed in discussion, though not without a sardonic edge, and prone to emotional reticence in moments of great distress. He carries a set of bones for divination, poison-tipped blow darts he deploys with deadly accuracy, and a hollow walking stick that conceals a knife. He is the close companion and protector of Simon, and rides the wolf Qantaqa, whom he raised from an abandoned pup.One of the three legendary swords, also known as Minneyar and Memory. According to accounts linked to Du Svardenvyrd and the Dwarrows, it was first forged from the keel of King Elvrit's boat after the Rimmersmen settled in Rimmersgard. Passed through the hands of northern rulers and later associated with Prester John, the sword became one of the great symbols of royal legend in Osten Ard.A Hernystiri monk and scholar of indeterminate order — known to claim membership of at least two different orders, and likely lying about both. Usually addressed as Brother Cadrach, he was born in the ancient Hernystiri city of Crannhyr and is stout and pink-faced with a weather-hardened complexion, small sharp grey eyes, and a monk's tonsure. Once a member of the League of the Scroll and regarded as promising enough to one day lead it, Cadrach fell into mounting fear and disillusionment as his studies brought him into contact with darker knowledge, and increasingly sought solace in drink. He eventually departed the League and vanished from scholarly circles, leaving most former colleagues to assume him dead. He now drifts through the world as a petty confidence man, adept at winning the trust of new companions only to con or rob them — though beneath the dissolute surface his intelligence, vast knowledge of Osten Ard, and abilities in the Art remain intact. He is a skilled horseman, versed in mechanical philosophy and some herblore, and an uneasy companion of Miriamele on her journeys.A legendary Nabbanai knight, born into the royal Benidrivine house as the son of Benidrivis-sá-Vinitta and elder brother of Duke Leobardis. Wielder of the great sword Thorn, he was High King Prester John's closest companion and greatest champion — widely regarded as the mightiest and most skilled warrior ever to walk Osten Ard. Their friendship began in unlikely fashion on the battlefield of Nearlaugh, where Camaris, then fifteen, took up his fallen uncle Ardrivus's sword against the conquering John; after a duel that ended in mutual respect, the two became inseparable. Though undisputed in his martial gifts, Camaris was by nature a pacifist who viewed fighting as a necessary burden rather than a glory. He was deeply religious, calm, and marked by a profound, inward sorrow. He bore the sword Thorn and the hunting horn Ti-tuno (also called Cellian), crafted at Mezutu'a from the fang of the dragon Hidohebhi. He is presumed by most of the world to have drowned at sea some forty years before the events of the trilogy.The Perdruinese proprietress of the inn Pelippa's Bowl in Kwanitupul, which she inherited from her aunt Xorastra. She is jut-jawed and combative in bearing, and her character is defined by greed, selfishness, and a chronic tendency to whine. She is a poor cook but a skilled negotiator where money is concerned. An Aedonite, she has little of her aunt's charitable spirit and a great deal of contempt for the establishment she was left with.A valley of Nabban known as a gateway into the duchy. Its valley floor is crowded with settlements and towns, and its hills are thick with whitewashed stone houses. It is connected with the Anitullean Road and the approach to Onestrine Pass.A walled coastal city in Hernystir. In older days the community was called Da-Yoshoga, or Goblin Rock, and the place preserves traces of older inhabitants and older names beneath its later Hernystiri identity.One of the Sithi Nine Cities, an abandoned Sithi city on the Aelfwent River on the east side of the Wealdhelm in Aldheorte. Its hidden, ancient character links it closely to the forest's Sithi past and to the older roads and rivers of Osten Ard.A young Erkynlander knight in his late twenties, knighted by Prince Josua and entirely devoted to his service. From a Hewenshire freeholding, he grew up working the fields alongside his older brother and sisters; he had little love for his father but holds his mother's memory fondly. Short, lank, dark hair and a habitually worn light blue coat mark him out. In character he is kind, loyal, and quietly ambitious — deeply committed to his prince yet unafraid to speak uncomfortable truths when Josua needs to hear them. An accomplished swordsman and skilled horseman, he rises to become Josua's second in command and is sometimes called the Prince's Right Hand.Father Dinivan is a Nabbanai Aedonite priest and the private secretary to Lector Ranessin, head of Mother Church — a position that places him at the intersection of many currents in Osten Ard's affairs. He is also a member of the League of the Scroll. Mostly shaved of head, with a remaining fringe of curly, grey-touched hair, bushy eyebrows, a boyish and homely intelligent face, and a habitual black robe, he makes an unassuming impression that belies the acuity behind it. He is clever, cautious, and jovial in equal measure, and genuinely kind — known by those close to him, including the Princess Miriamele, for offering honest counsel where others bring only flattery. He is versed in some degree of the Art and thoroughly schooled in Aedonite scripture and mythology. He carries the signet ring of Lector Ranessin and wears the golden scroll-and-quill pendant of a Scrollbearer.A Hernystiri woman originally named Efiathe and remembered as the Rose of Hernysadharc. She married Prester John despite being much younger than him and became Queen of Osten Ard. Her place in the royal household connects her to Elias and Josua, and the wiki presents her as a figure whose beauty and presence deeply affected those closest to the High King's court.An Erkynlander prince, first-born son of High King Prester John, Prince Regent of Osten Ard, Liege-Lord of Meremund, and heir apparent to the High King's throne. Around forty years old at the beginning of The Dragonbone Chair, he is powerfully built, with black hair, green eyes, a high brow, and a hawklike nose, and he commonly dresses in black and green. Elias is forceful, boisterous, and commanding, but also increasingly temperamental and suspicious. His strained relationship with his younger brother Josua and his reliance on the priest Pryrates place him at the center of the realm's growing political unease.The Summer City of the Sithi, one of the Sithi Nine Cities, standing in the southeastern corner of Aldheorte forest near the border of the High Thrithings grasslands. It was once a thriving Sithi city and remains an important name in the geography of the Gardenborn.Count of Nad Mullach and kinsman of King Lluth of Hernystir, a Hernystiri nobleman and diplomat of considerable standing. He grew up in native Nad Mullach, at the conjoining of the Inniscrich and Cuihmne rivers in western Hernystir, and was invested with his territories young, pledging loyalty to Lluth when barely twenty-two. He has since served as one of Lluth's most trusted emissaries, earning wide esteem for his bravery and wisdom. Lean-featured, with high thin cheekbones, a high forehead, and long black hair, he carries himself with courtly refinement that conceals, in Isgrimnur's words, a resolve "hard as shield-steel." He is dutiful and composed, and has known Maegwin, Lluth's daughter, since her girlhood. There is speculation that some noble families of Hernystir, Eolair's among them, carry a trace of Sithi blood.The capital city of Erkynland, adjacent to the Hayholt. It is the chief city of the kingdom and part of the political and royal center of Osten Ard.A kingdom on the western coast of Osten Ard, ruled from the Hayholt. It is bounded by Hernystir, Rimmersgard, Aldheorte, the Thrithings, and Nabban, making it a central political region between many peoples, roads, forests, rivers, and borderlands.An inhabitant of Erkynland, counted among the human peoples of Osten Ard. Erkynlanders are associated with Westerling and Erkynlandish speech, and their notable figures include Prince Josua.A wool-producing city in Erkynland, southeast of Erchester. Its prosperity and civic life are tied to the wool trade, placing it among the significant Erkynlandish towns and cities beyond the Hayholt.Earl of Falshire, later elevated by King Elias to Duke of Falshire, Utanyeat, and the Westfold, an Erkynlander nobleman and one of Elias's closest confidants. He has long black hair and carries himself with the swagger of a man who expects the world to accommodate his ambitions. Ambitious, cruel, and deeply narcissistic, his overconfidence is remarked upon even by those who share his allegiances. He was at Elias's side at the coronation festivities, drinking heavily and behaving with the rowdiness he mistakes for vigour. Elias promised him the hand of Princess Miriamele — an arrangement she deeply resented. When the wool weavers of Falshire revolted against the new king's taxes, he put down the uprising with extraordinary cruelty, burning the district and executing the guild leaders in vats of hot oil. He is thereafter employed as one of Elias's chief instruments of enforcement across the realm.March-thane of the Stallion Clan and supreme ruler of all the Three Thrithings, a position he secured through alliance with Prester John during the Thrithings Wars and holds through fear and brute strength rather than respect. He is a large and formidable man: long black beard knotted into two thick braids, hair faintly striped with silver, a wide frame knotted with muscle, huge hands laden with rings and bracelets, and crooked teeth — appearing at least sixty years of age, yet still powerfully fit. He is quick to anger, cruel, strong-willed, and deeply duplicitous. He is the father of Vorzheva, whom he had intended to sell in marriage for thirteen horses to a man named Utvart; when Vorzheva fled with Prince Josua instead, Fikolmij lost both the bride-price and a great deal of pride, an affront he did not forgive. He also has a younger daughter, Hyara.The natural and fantastical life of Osten Ard, ranging from common plants and animals to stranger creatures of legend and lore. Its flora includes croques, fire-poppies, hollyhocks, lilies, marigolds, quickweed, snowdrops, starblooms, sunflowers, wintercap, mistletoe, witchwood, alder, apple, ash, banyan, birch, cedar, fig, hazelnut, hemlock, linden, mangroves, oak, rowan, sand-palm, spruce, oats, wheat, cattails, lutegrass, yellowroot, and corn. Its fauna includes fish, reptiles, amphibians, mammals, birds, insects, dragons, cave borers, ghants, kilpa, and other uncanny creatures.An Erkynlander blacksmith and native of Falshire, elected constable of New Gadrinsett among Josua's company. Young, stocky, and broad-shouldered, he has the wary heavy-lidded look of a veteran street fighter, a face liberally scarred, a rough voice, a gap in his teeth, and two fingers missing. He is clever and plainspoken, skilled in metalworking, woodworking, and weapons crafting — he fashioned a short sword for Miriamele. His father was Freobeorn; his wife and children were killed in the razing of Falshire by Fengbald's troops, a loss that drives his fierce and personal hatred of the Duke.A squatter town near the junction of the Stefflod and Ymstrecca, settled by refugees from Erkynland. Its rough origin as a refuge settlement gives it a different character from the older cities and baronies of the realm.The Niskie kilpa-singer of the ship Eadne Cloud, a member of the Tinukeda'ya people. Ancient, slight, and frail in appearance, she has pale golden skin netted with wrinkles, wide-set dark eyes, a fringe of white hair, and thin brows. Her character is clever, patient, honourable, and deeply kind, though marked by a pervasive tiredness. By the events of the story she is a great-grandmother more than twenty times over, from one of the largest Niskie families. Her principal skill is kilpa-singing — the ability to influence the mood of the sea-creatures called kilpa through song, ordinarily used to keep them at bay. She takes a genuine liking to Miriamele and tells her she can be trusted.The Sithi-built main tower of the Hayholt, once the tallest tower of Asu'a and the last remnant of the old Sithi city visible above ground. Also formerly called Nightingale Tower, it is described as cloud-tall, with white walls, a bell tower of tall arched openings, and stairs that climb upward as well as descend deep beneath the city. Its place at the heart of the Hayholt ties it to the ancient Gardenborn past beneath Erkynland's royal castle.Earl of Utanyeat and High King's Hand to Elias, an Erkynlander nobleman who has been Elias's close friend since youth, sharing battles and adventures across many years. Green-eyed, with greying hair cut short, he is clever, shrewd, and deeply loyal, though intolerant of disrespect from those beneath him. He served Elias faithfully through the early years of his reign, and Elias has privately declared him the only man he truly trusts. Guthwulf, for his part, watches the growing influence of Pryrates over the king with increasing unease.Duchess of Elvritshalla and wife of Duke Isgrimnur, a Rimmersman noblewoman of sharp eyes and red cheeks. Stern, caring, and motherly by nature, she is also temperamental, fussy, and possessed of considerable courage and practical competence. She ran the household at Elvritshalla through the many long absences of her husband, raised their children — including Isorn and three others — and is described by Isgrimnur as a part of himself, the two of them grown together "like two old trees." A capable midwife and manager of a great household, she proves herself resourceful and resilient when adversity demands it.Prince and Duke of Hernystir-Duchy, son of King Lluth and his wife Fiathna, and half-brother of Maegwin through their father. He has long sorrel-coloured hair, is handsome and tall, and is five years younger than Maegwin. Impulsive, temperamental, and prideful, he burns with love for his people and his land. He is quick to act on that passion: when Guthwulf delivered threatening demands to Lluth's court on behalf of Elias, Gwythinn drew his sword and held it to the High King's Hand's throat before his father ordered him to stand down.An Erkynlander soldier serving as captain of the guards at Naglimund, assigned by Prince Josua to personally train Simon on his arrival. Burly, broad-backed, and bearlike, with a brown curly beard, he is a simple, hearty man of steady reliability. He becomes something of a protector to Simon on the perilous journey north in search of the sword Thorn, remaining steadfast through every trial the road presents. He had a wife; their only child died in infancy.The great castle of Erkynland, standing above Kynslagh Bay and the city of Erchester. Built over the ruins of the former Sithi city Asu'a, it contains layers of construction from several peoples and ages, including a vast hidden labyrinth of older Sithi and Dwarrow structures beneath its human halls. Its most famous surviving remnant of Sithi architecture is Green Angel Tower, and its position makes it the royal and political heart of Osten Ard.A Rimmersman monk of the order of Saint Hoderund, encountered by Simon and Binabik in the aftermath of the sacking of Saint Hoderund's abbey by Ingen Jegger's forces. He is argumentative and proud, his relations with the Qanuc troll Binabik immediately marked by the ancient mutual hostility between Rimmersmen and Troll folk. He tends to two monks who survived the raid and buries the one who dies, quarrelling bitterly with Binabik throughout.A largely mountainous kingdom bordering Erkynland to the west. Although nominally independent, it acknowledges the suzerainty of the High King. Its people are described as pagan, and its chief places include Hernysadharc, Crannhyr, Nad Mullach, Abaingeat, Ballacym, and Cathyn Dair.The inhabitants of Hernystir, a human people whose language is Hernystiri and whose old religion is considered pagan by Aedonites. Their kingdom's name is tied to Hern, whose people received lands and royal arms in the Dawn Time, when the Keida'ya still ruled directly over the lands of men. Hernystiri society is feudal; Hernystir was once an independent kingdom and later became a vassal of the High King. Notable Hernystiri include Eolair, Lluth, Maegwin, Gwythinn, Penemhwye, Fiathna, Inahwen, and Craobhan.One of the Sithi Nine Cities, an abandoned Dwarrow city beneath Rimmersgard's Vestivegg Mountains. After the parting of the Sithi and Norns, Jenjiyana of the Nightingales declared it one of the cities given to the Tinukeda'ya.A Rimmersman king, son of Fingil, and the second of the Six Kings of the Hayholt, counted among the so-called Northern Kings. Known as King Hjeldin the Mad, he was interested in strange arts and allowed his helper-priest Nisses to pursue unusual researches. He is remembered in the Six Kings Rhyme and is closely associated with Hjeldin's Tower at the Hayholt.A Thrithings-man and Randwarder who leaves Fikolmij's service to join Prince Josua at Sesuad'ra. He serves as a messenger between Josua and other commanders in the field.Large, shaggy, manlike beings of the Tinukeda'ya people — called giants by most races of Osten Ard and hojun in their own tongue. They were bred apart from the other Tinukeda'ya by the Keida'ya long before their coming to Osten Ard. They are said never to stop growing, and may live at least three hundred years. Their fur is usually white, their skin darker beneath it, their tongues grey, their voices deep and rumbling, their teeth sharp. Some individuals have two heads. They are capable of learning language. Those who dwelt too close to Jao é-Tinukai'i were hunted by the Sithi; those encountered near Nakkiga were enslaved by the Hikeda'ya as war beasts. They are a recurring and dangerous presence in the high mountains of Osten Ard.Younger daughter of March-thane Fikolmij and younger sister of Vorzheva, a woman of the Thrithings tied to the ruling family of Clan Mehrdon.A wandering people known chiefly as horse-traders and generally regarded as disreputable. They are associated with unsettled travel, trade in horses, and a harsh reputation among other peoples.A great white ice dragon dwelling at the peak of the mountain Urmsheim, daughter of Hidohebhi and sister of Shurakai, with Khaerukama'o as her grandfather. She has served as a boogeyman in the stories of those who live near Urmsheim, with many uncertain whether she still lives. Her appearance is fearsome: a snakelike head as long as a man is tall, piercing blue eyes, a whip-like tail, aged yellowed fur on her back and legs with white scales elsewhere, and black throat, tongue, and blood. She is animalistic in nature.An Erkynlander of enormous stature who works at the Hayholt, initially as a heavy-lifting assistant to Doctor Morgenes, later elevated to Master of the Great Inferno — the foundry beneath the castle — a position he relishes and refers to with the self-granted title of Doctor Inch. Hugely tall, though with a hunched posture that sets his head barely above his breastbone, he has a round vacant face, spiky black hair clumsily cut, a whiskered jaw, a voice thick and slow, and breath that smells of stone. His face is later scarred by forge flames, and he is missing one eye. He is dim-witted, temperamental, and profoundly cruel, with no visible capacity for empathy. As foundry master he runs his workers as slaves, punishing any who falter, and is feared throughout the lower reaches of the Hayholt.A Sithi prince of an age long past, son of Iyu'unigato and Amerasu and brother of Hakatri. In life he was handsome, tall even by the standards of his race, with straight black hair; his personality was fond of wit but easily stung by others' teasing, impatient, and impulsive. His name in Sithi means "Here is bright speech." With his brother he slew the black dragon Hidohebhi — a victory that cost many lives and left Hakatri maimed by dragon's blood. The shame and guilt of that event, combined with his fury at the mortal allies he blamed for abandoning them, curdled his character beyond redemption. During the fall of Asu'a before the armies of men, Ineluki forged the sword Sorrow in the city's own fires, an act that consumed his mortal life and killed many around him. His spirit endured, however, and as the Storm King he now exerts a malevolent influence over Osten Ard — working through living agents and causing a spreading, worsening winter across the land.A Black Rimmersman and the Queen's Huntsman of the Norn queen Utuk'ku — the first mortal ever to hold that title, a distinction he bears with fierce pride. Powerfully built, cold-faced, with hair so pale yellow it appears white and eyes of a colourless, possibly blue, hue, he wears a black wolf helmet given to him by Utuk'ku herself as a mark of his station. He is devoted to the queen with an absolute loyalty that admits no other consideration. He is master of the Norn hounds and a relentless tracker, pursuing his quarry across vast distances with implacable patience.Duke of Elvritshalla and one of the great lords of Rimmersgard, a Rimmersman of notable height with huge gnarled hands, a grey beard braided but often tangled from habitual tugging, and a swiftness of movement that surprises those who underestimate his age and stature. He is the son of Isbeorn, from whom he inherited the duchy, and the husband of Gutrun, with whom he shares four children including his eldest son Isorn. He is a cousin of Skali Sharp-nose of Kaldskryke. An Aedonite — his father was the first of his line to convert — he is fiercely loyal, blunt, deeply caring, and driven by a strong sense of honour. Prester John once described him as having "the heart of a bear and the wit of an ox," which he recalls with rueful affection. A trusted friend of Prester John and an uncle-figure to both Elias and Josua, he carries a war-hammer alongside his sword. He is among the tallest figures in Osten Ard.Eldest son of Duke Isgrimnur and Gutrun, heir to Elvritshalla, a Rimmersman with the same blue eyes as his father, broad features, a drawn and shadowed look, and a stock-shouldered, bulky frame. A pious Aedonite, he is skilled with sword and horse. He is on friendly terms with Count Eolair of Hernystir.A mythical forest bandit, remembered as a figure of outlaw legend rather than as a courtly or noble personage.A hidden Sithi settlement deep in the Aldheorte, its name meaning "Boat on the Ocean of Trees." It is made of elaborate fabric rather than stone and is woven into the forest itself. Notable features include Shao Irigú, the Summer Gate of two towering hemlocks, and the Yásira, a great tent raised around a vast ash tree.A Rimmersman and member of the League of the Scroll, called "Iron Eyes." Old, with fierce blue eyes and white hair, he is a man of wisdom and a keeper of deep lore. His father Trestolt was a Scrollbearer before him. He possesses an ability to see great distances, possibly a form of the Art. He travels to Naglimund to deliver urgent warnings about the threat of the Storm King, and assists in unravelling the ancient lore surrounding the three great swords from passages of Du Svardenvyrd.An Erkynlander boy from the Hayholt, apprenticed to the chandler Jakob. Slow and stumpy, pale, with fine blond hair and a treble chin — though he grows more handsome as he matures and slims down. He is pessimistic, earnest, and shy. His father died of the chest-fever. He is a childhood friend of Simon, having trained alongside him in hopes of becoming a soldier; later he becomes Simon's squire. He is skilled in chandlery, forging, message-running, and singing, with a basic grounding in swordsmanship.One of the Sithi Nine Cities, now beneath the southern seas. After the parting of the Sithi and Norns, Jenjiyana of the Nightingales declared it one of the cities given to the Tinukeda'ya.A Sithi prince of Jao é-Tinukai'i, born after the fall of Asu'a and counted among the younger members of his people. Son of Shima'onari and Likimeya, brother of Aditu, and great-nephew of Ineluki. He has golden-brown skin, amber-flecked eyes, and lavender-blue dyed hair, and moves with the fluid, catlike grace characteristic of the Sithi. Together with his sister Aditu he befriended the scholar Tanahaya in their youth. He wields the witchwood sword Indreju. His friendship with Simon began when Simon freed him from a cotsman's trap in the Aldheorte forest; in return, Jiriki loosed a white arrow (Staja Ame) into a nearby tree — the Sithi sign of a life-debt owed.An Erkynlander prince, Prince of Erkynland and Liege-Lord of Naglimund, younger brother of Elias and uncle to Miriamele. Around thirty-eight at the beginning of The Dragonbone Chair, he is tall and slender, with close-cropped brown hair, a high forehead, hawklike nose, pale grey eyes, and a preference for greyish clothing over royal splendor. Called Josua Lackhand because he lost his right hand in a skirmish, he remains a capable swordsman with the slim blade Naidel. Quiet, brooding, studious, melancholy, and self-doubting, he has little desire for power, but his position and conscience make him an important figure in the troubles surrounding the High King's realm.One of the Sithi Nine Cities, apparently on or near Warinsten. It is associated with Benayha and with the ancient geography of the Gardenborn, though its exact fate is uncertain.A Sitha who accompanies Simon and Jiriki's party to Urmsheim along with Sijandi. He remains at the foot of the mountain to care for the horses.A large trading city at the edge of the Wran. It began as a small trading village and grew when merchants from the Southern Islands, Perdruin, and Nabban made use of its position near the marshlands and waterways.The lake on whose shore stands the Hayholt. Its position beside the great castle ties it to the royal and legendary geography of Erkynland.An Erkynlander girl, Miriamele's handmaid, and companion of Geloë. Small and pale, with dark brown eyes, she becomes quiet in the physical world after an attack by Ingen Jegger's hounds, but is far more expressive on the road of dreams. She has an unusual connection to dream-roads and visions, where she appears happiest and most alive, and is cared for by Geloë while remaining close to Miriamele, Simon, Jeremias, Aditu, and Gutrun.Duke of Nabban, a Nabbanai nobleman of the Benidrivine line and brother of Camaris. By the time of The Dragonbone Chair he has long white hair, pink cheeks, mild blue eyes, and a reputation for kindness in Miriamele's memory. He enjoys music and is close to the Aedonite Church. As tensions rise between Elias, Josua, and Nabban, Leobardis attempts to assess the realm's shifting loyalties, sending Baron Devasalles to Naglimund to judge Josua's cause while those nearest him press competing political interests. His house's crest is the golden kingfisher, and his flagship is Emettin's Jewel.A Thrithings-man mercenary chieftain in Fengbald's pay, associated with the armed companies serving the Duke's campaign.King of Hernystir, father of Gwythinn and Maegwin. A Hernystiri ruler with a grey moustache, mobile clever features, a crooked nose broken in boyhood, and a lined face, Lluth is described as usually joyful and smiling, deeply loving of his people and land. He hosts Guthwulf and the Erkynguard at the Taig when Elias's demands reach Hernystir, and his court includes close liegemen such as Eolair. His family ties include his father Llythinn, his cousin Ebekah, his first wife Penemhwye, his later wives Fiathna and Inahwen, and his children Maegwin and Gwythinn.A hill and the site of Hernysadharc. It was given to Hern after a dispute arising from Azosha's bequest of the land to Hern's mortal people, linking the place to ancient dealings between mortals and the Sithi.Princess of Hernystir, daughter of King Lluth and Penemhwye, and half-sister of Gwythinn. Tall, long-legged, and sorrel-haired, she is insecure about her height and painfully uncertain of Eolair's feelings for her, yet she is also kind, gentle, sensitive, strong, and respected by her people. Lluth trusts her to lead in his absence, and the Hernystiri value her fairness and good judgment. She has skill with animal husbandry, keeps a carved Nightingale token from Lluth, and experiences visions or the road of dreams through the lens of Hernystiri belief.The human race living throughout Osten Ard. Humans came across the sea to settle in Osten Ard well after the Sithi had established themselves as masters of the continent. Human peoples include Erkynlanders, Hernystiri, Nabbanai, Perdruinese, Rimmersmen, Thrithings-men, Wrannamen, Hyrka, and the people of Nascadu. The Sithi call mankind Sudhoda'ya, meaning Sunset Children.A city in Erkynland on the northern mouth of the Gleniwent, opposite Wentmouth. It is associated with the Prince Regent Elias and with Princess Miriamele's early life.One of the Sithi Nine Cities, known as the Silverhome, located beneath the Grianspog Mountains. It is still occupied by a small group of Dwarrow and includes named places such as the Arena and Pattern Hall. After the parting of the Sithi and Norns, Jenjiyana of the Nightingales declared Mezutu'a to be given to the Tinukeda'ya.A Qanuc village in Yiqanuc, birthplace of Binabik and domain of the Qanuc folk. It is effectively governed by the Herder and the Huntress, Uammannaq and Nunuuika, and stands as one of the central named settlements of the Trollfells.An Erkynlander princess, only child and heiress of King Elias and his Nabbanai wife Hylissa. Slender, green-eyed, golden-haired, and gifted with a lovely singing voice, she is kind, guarded, empathetic, clever, and altruistic, though troubled by her father's growing distance under Pryrates's influence. Miriamele often disguises herself, using the name Malachias when passing as a boy and Marya when passing as a servant. Though high-born, she proves resourceful and capable in travel, danger, and courtly maneuvering.A valley deep in the heart of Aldheorte Forest, called Tanakirú in the Zida'ya language. It is associated with strange forest lore, including the Uro'eni, the Ogre of Misty Vale.An Erkynlander doctor, scholar, court physician at the Hayholt, and member of the League of the Scroll. Short, blue-eyed, white-haired, with long bent fingers and a sparse beard, he is intelligent, temperamental, particular, and jovial. He lives in a converted barracks in the Middle Bailey and writes The Life and Reign of King John Presbyter, a manuscript containing many secrets of Osten Ard. A practitioner of the Art, he takes Simon as an apprentice, teaches him reading, lore, and caution rather than easy magic, and serves as one of the boy's closest guardians.<b>Disambiguation:</b><br>• <a href="bword://Nabban (duchy)">Nabban (duchy)</a> - Duchy on the central western coast of Osten Ard, one of the major human powers of the continent<br>• <a href="bword://Nabban (city)">Nabban (city)</a> - Capital and largest city of the Duchy of Nabban, chief urban center of Nabbanai powerThe capital and largest city of the Duchy of Nabban. It is the chief urban center of Nabbanai power and one of the principal cities of Osten Ard.A city and duchy on the central western coast of Osten Ard. The duchy is one of the major human powers of the continent, with its capital, outer baronies, valleys, bays, roads, and noble houses forming a distinct Nabbanai political and cultural world.The inhabitants of Nabban, one of the human peoples of Osten Ard. They have their own Nabbanai tongue and a distinct culture within mankind. Notable Nabbanai include nobles, priests, and members of the Benidrivine and Ingadarine families.A fortress and town in northern Erkynland at the base of the Wealdhelm. Domain of Prince Josua, it bears the grey swan as banner and sigil and is said to be a place of great power, comparable in some ways to a Master Witness.The Norn city inside Stormspike. The Norns moved there after abandoning Nakkiga-That-Was, carving their home into the mountain and making it the hidden seat of Hikeda'ya power.One of the Sithi Nine Cities, a ruined Norn city at the foot of Stormspike. It was abandoned when the Norns moved into the caverns they carved beneath the mountain, the place also called Nakkiga.An island nation at the southern end of the Bay of Firannos. Its culture is associated with piracy, mercenaries, and slavery, and its people are described as dark-skinned and dark-haired, with an exotic language.A desert region in the southernmost reaches of Osten Ard. It is described as a dry, barren wasteland of sand dunes, inhabited by creatures such as apes, lions, and sand snakes.Duchess of Nabban, wife of Duke Leobardis, mother of Benigaris, Varellan, and Antippa, and sister of Hylissa. A sternly beautiful Nabbanai noblewoman, she is a shrewd manipulator and politician, with high aspirations and a strong command of courtly presentation through clothing, hairdressing, makeup, and servants. Anyone dealing with the Nabbanai throne must account not only for Leobardis or Benigaris but also for Nessalanta. She is egotistical, superstitious, politically forceful, and interested in astrology.A settlement of Josua's followers on Sesuad'ra, named after Gadrinsett in the valley to the west. It is a refuge community rather than an old city, shaped by displacement and the gathering of allies.A half-human Norn and Queen's Talon, daughter of Viyeki and Tzoja. The first and only child of her parents, she is fierce and independent from her earliest days and devoted to making her father proud even when she disagrees with his hopes for her life. Her father's wife Khimabu is her official mother, though their relationship is cool. Like other Hikeda'ya children she is sorted for service, and her unusual survival of that ordeal leads her into the Order of Sacrifice. Her known possession is the sword Cold Root.An Aedonite Black Rimmersman priest who served King Fingil and later King Hjeldin. He is associated with esoteric learning and with the old northern court of the Hayholt, where his knowledge made him an adviser in matters beyond ordinary priestly counsel. During Hjeldin's reign he wrote Du Svardenvyrd, also known as The Weird of Swords, a work later judged heretical and unholy by the Sancellan Aedonitus but preserved in secret rather than destroyed.An immortal, human-like Gardenborn people also called the Hikeda'ya, or Cloud Children. Originally part of the Keida'ya with the Sithi, they came from the Garden across the sea to Osten Ard and became distinct from the Zida'ya. They are very pale or ghost-like, with white hair and dark purplish-black eyes. Their culture is centered on Queen Utuk'ku, whom many regard as inseparable from the Hikeda'ya race itself, and on service through formal Orders such as Builders, Sacrifice, Anchoresses, Celebrants, Chroniclers, Singers, and others. Their society is hierarchical, clan-based, and austere, with white or colorless clothing.A Qanuc wise-man, scholar, Singing Man of Mintahoq and the mountains of Yiqanuc, Scrollbearer, and master of Binabik. Very fat and troll-sized, he is remembered chiefly for his wisdom, his teaching, and his correspondence with Doctor Morgenes. He taught Morgenes how to make birds carry messages, and sets out south with Binabik after signs, bone-castings, and news from Morgenes trouble him. As Singing Man, he stands at the intersection of song, lore, medicine, ceremony, and ancient knowledge among the Qanuc.The world in which Memory, Sorrow and Thorn takes place. It is a vast land of varied terrain and climate, containing human kingdoms, Gardenborn ruins, forests, mountains, rivers, bays, deserts, marshes, ancient roads, and hidden places.An inn in Kwanitupul named for Saint Pelippa because it was run by Xorastra, a woman who had once been a nun of Pelippa's order. After Xorastra, the inn passes to her niece Charystra. It is large, undistinguished-looking, and located in a backwater part of the warehouse district beneath a sign with a golden bowl.A Hernystiri woman, first wife of King Lluth and mother of Maegwin, remembered through her place in the royal household of Hernystir.An island duchy west of Nabban, ruled from Ansis Pelippé. Its position off the coast gives it a distinctive maritime and political role among the powers of Osten Ard.An inhabitant of Perdruin, associated with the Perdruinese language and also with King John's Westerling tongue after his conquest of Osten Ard. Notable Perdruinese include Sir Tallistro, Count Streáwe, and Lady Faiera.High King of Osten Ard, Seventh King of the Hayholt, and wielder of the sword Bright-Nail, also called Minneyar or Memory. Born on Warinsten as a commoner, he rose to become the king who brought the realm many years of stability and peace and was remembered for loving his people. In youth he was golden-haired; in character he is reckless, battle-loving, pragmatic, ardently Aedonite, and hostile to the Sithi. His reign bound Nabban, Rimmersgard, Hernystir, and the Thrithings into the political order of the High Ward, and his friendships included Camaris, Isgrimnur, and Towser.A hairless, pale, scarlet-robed priest associated with dark magic and the Art, possibly of Naraxi origin. Cruel, manipulative, and cold-eyed, he takes pleasure in pain and is willing to feign subservience when useful. Once considered for the League of the Scroll, he was expelled for his interest in dangerous subjects. He becomes closely tied to Elias, works from Hjeldin's Tower and the Hayholt, and pursues hidden lore, alchemy, necromancy, and Words of Changing with heedless appetite.A wolf, Binabik's companion, mount, and friend. She travels with him through the dangers surrounding Simon, Josua's company, and the wider struggle across Osten Ard.A diminutive human-like people living in the mountains of Yiqanuc, also called trolls. They are much smaller than ordinary humans and maintain distinctive customs around adulthood, marriage, law, religion, and song. A Qanuc man proposes by placing his spear before a woman's door; adulthood includes a Walk of Manhood or Womanhood; serious disputes may be judged by the Herder and Huntress in the Cave of the Ancestor. Their Singing Men preserve songs, ceremonies, medicine, priestly knowledge, and written lore on hide scrolls. Notable Qanuc include Binabik, Ookequk, Sisqinanamook, Nunuuika, Uammannaq, Chukku, Qangolik, and Snenneq.Mistress of Chambermaids at the Hayholt, an Erkynlander woman and foster mother of Simon. Called Rachel the Dragon by Simon, she is older, stern, devoutly Aedonite, obsessed with cleanliness, convinced of the value of hard work, and formidable to lazy scullions. Rachel helps raise Simon with the other chambermaids and Morgenes. Her practical authority, knowledge of the Hayholt, and fierce maternal concern make her one of the castle's most memorable servants.Lector of the Aedonite Church, born Oswine of Stanshire in Erkynland and raised to the highest office of Mother Church through Prester John's influence. Nearly seventy, slender, pale, grey-haired, and bright-eyed, he is gentle, humble, extremely clever, and a fearsome debater. He dislikes pomp, preferring to walk rather than be carried on ceremonial occasions, and attempts to remain outwardly neutral amid political conflict while working subtly for peace. Father Dinivan serves as his secretary.The land of the Rimmersmen in northern Osten Ard. It is a cold northern region associated with Elvritshalla, Naarved, Saegard, Skoggey, Tungoldyr, Hullnir, and the lands in the shadow of Stormspike.The inhabitants of Rimmersgard. Most converted to the Aedonite Church after King John's conquest, though historically they followed Rimmersman paganism. They are associated with a cold northern homeland, common use of furs, and the language Rimmerspakk. Notable Rimmersmen include Gutrun, Hengfisk, Ingen Jegger, Isgrimnur, Isorn, Jarnauga, Skali, and Sludig.An Erkynlander harper and musician at Josua's court in Naglimund. Young, slender, dark-haired, fond of fine clothing, and skilled with harp, lute, and song, he has a wide knowledge of the songs and stories of Osten Ard. Boisterous, anxious, mischievous, and not especially brave, he is nevertheless loyal to Josua and perceptive about the prince's self-doubt, often wishing Josua would act more firmly. He befriends Simon and spends much time in the company of the old jester Towser.Baron of Metessa, a Nabbanai nobleman whose barony lies north of Lake Clodu and borders the Lake Thrithings. Also known in Nabbanai as Seriddan Metessis, he is older brother of Brindalles and uncle of Pasevalles. He has shrewd eyes, a sun-browned bearded peasant face, and a roguishly dangerous look unusual among Nabbanai nobles. His lands are prosperous, crossed by a branch of the Stefflod, and centered on the hilltop keep Chasu Metessa. The heraldic bird of the Metessans is a blue heron.The Stone of Farewell, south of Enki-e-Shao'saye, standing atop Rhao iye-Sama'an five hundred cubits above the river. It is the site of the parting of Sithi and Norns and one of the most important ancient places in Osten Ard.A red dragon associated with the Hayholt and later with the Dragonbone Chair made from her bones. Huge as a house, with red-golden scales and teeth as long as Simon's hand, she is a daughter of Hidohebhi and sister of Igjarjuk. Her lair lies deep in the older history beneath the Hayholt, and royal legend links Prester John to her remains. Her blood is caustic enough to burn through flesh and bone, and she breathes fire.A Sitha who accompanies Simon and Jiriki's party to Urmsheim along with Kiushapo. Like Kiushapo, he remains at the foot of the mountain to care for the horses.A young Erkynlander, born Seoman and called Simon, fourteen years old at the beginning of The Dragonbone Chair. Red-haired, freckled, blue-eyed, tall and thin-framed, he is a scullion at the Hayholt raised by Rachel and watched over by Doctor Morgenes. Naive, anxious, childish, brave, and prone to daydreaming, he hungers for stories, glory, and magic. Morgenes takes him as an apprentice, teaching reading, herbs, history, and caution rather than the easy wizardry Simon imagines. His curiosity about the Hayholt's hidden ways draws him into the larger mysteries of Osten Ard.A Perdruinese boatman living on the coast above the Wran. He transports Isgrimnur to Kwanitupul.A Qanuc warrior, daughter of Uammannaq the Herder and Nunuuika the Huntress, rulers of Yiqanuc, and betrothed to Binabik. She has glossy black hair plaited on either side of her face and joined beneath her chin with a sky-blue ribbon, brown skin, little jewelry, and a single blue gem on her forehead held by a leather thong. Strong-willed, comely, and clever, she is a notable Qanuc woman whose family ties place her close to the leadership of her people.An immortal, human-like Gardenborn people who came to Osten Ard long before humanity. They call themselves Zida'ya, or Dawn Children, while humans know them as Sithi and Hernystiri call them the Peaceful Ones. Golden-skinned, slender, graceful, with large amber cat-like eyes, prominent cheekbones, and naturally white hair often dyed bright colors, they do not age as mortals do. Their history begins in the Garden with the Keida'ya, later divided between Zida'ya and Hikeda'ya, and continues through exile across the sea, the founding of great cities, conflict and friendship with mortal peoples, and hidden refuges such as Jao é-Tinukai'i.The nine great cities founded by the Gardenborn after they fled Venyha Do'sae, the Lost Garden. They were masterworks as well as homes for the Sithi, Norns, and their kin: Asu'a, Da'ai Chikiza, Enki-e-Shao'saye, Hikehikayo, Jhiná T'seneí, Kementari, Mezutu'a, Nakkiga-That-Was, and Tumet'ai.A Rimmersman thane of Kaldskryke and kinsman of Duke Isgrimnur, called Sharp-nose. Yellow-bearded and politically favored by Elias at Isgrimnur's expense, he leads a destructive campaign against King Lluth and the Hernystiri, driving them into the mountains.A Rimmersman soldier in Duke Isgrimnur's service and companion of Simon and Binabik from Naglimund. Fair-haired, yellow-bearded, pale blue-eyed, dutiful, pragmatic, and clever, he is initially wary of close fellowship, especially with a Qanuc troll, but proves a resilient travel companion. Sent with the party seeking the sword Thorn, he journeys through danger, imprisonment, and pursuit, and teaches Simon practical combat lessons on the road. Around campfires he sometimes sings both bawdy and heartfelt songs.An abandoned town in the White Waste, east of Saint Skendi's monastery. Its location places it among the bleak northern Erkynlandish settlements near the edge of the great forest and the waste.A mountain in the North and home of the Norns. The city of Nakkiga is located inside the mountain, making Stormspike both a natural feature and the center of Hikeda'ya power.Father Strangyeard, an Erkynlander Aedonite priest, scholar, archivist, and historian at Naglimund. Slight, pale, long-chinned, with sparse red hair, one blue eye, and a black eyepatch, he is shy, bumbling, distracted, and highly intelligent. He researches the prophecy of the three swords with Jarnauga, carries and studies Morgenes's manuscript The Life and Reign of King John Presbyter, and becomes a Scrollbearer. His strengths are scholarship, archives, and patient lore-work rather than worldly confidence.Count of Perdruin, lord of Ansis Pelippé and master of the island. White-haired, aged, physically frail, and carried in a litter because his legs no longer work, he is nevertheless iron-willed, manipulative, jovial, temperamental, and supremely skilled at politics. He presents weakness when useful and uses Perdruin's neutrality, information networks, wealth, servants, gardens, and trained messenger birds to bargain with every side. One of the wealthiest men in Osten Ard, he believes those lacking physical strength must survive through intelligence.A famous Perdruinese knight of John Presbyter's Great Table, remembered in connection with the First Thrithings War.A mysterious group of Tinukeda'ya living in Nakkiga, associated with Jijibo's experiments. They are grotesquely varied in body shape, with limbs and orifices in strange places, aversion to bright light, and the ability to speak. Named figures include Naya Nos, Dasa, and Uvasika, called Mistress of the Hidden and the Silent Lady.A grassy dipping place in Aldheorte, called Ereb Irgú or Western Gate by the Sithi. It was the site of a major battle between Hernystiri and Rimmersmen during the Rimmersman invasions of Osten Ard, and its common name is thought to come from the Rimmersman Knokkegard, "the Boneyard."A mystical dream realm in which those who can travel there are able to communicate with one another and discover truths about the world. It is a place of vision, contact, and hidden knowledge rather than an ordinary road.A permafrost region north of Aldheorte Forest in Erkynland. It is one of the bleak northern reaches of Osten Ard.The nomadic clans-people of the Three Thrithings, also called randwarders. Their wagon-travelling culture is strongly centered on horses, with wealth measured by herd quality and size, and strength viewed as the paramount measure of a man. Thrithings society is heavily male-dominated, suspicious of town-dwelling "stone-dwellers," and governed by old clan laws concerning leadership, marriage, and custom. Clans gather at Blood Lake for the Thanemoot, a midsummer festival with markets, contests, riding, wrestling, and other feats. Notable Thrithings-folk include Vorzheva, Fikolmij, Hotvig, Hyara, and Lezhdraka.A Wrannaman scholar and member of the League of the Scroll. Short and brown-skinned, scholarly, skeptical of religion, and somewhat alienated from his own people, he was the first of his village to leave the Wran to study with the Usirean Brothers in Ansis Pelippé. There he learned Nabbanai and befriended Doctor Morgenes, whom he came to revere. Tiamak studies healing lore and works on The Sovran Remedies of the Wranna Healers, exchanging letters by messenger bird with other scholars. He can travel the Wran on stilts and is fluent in Perdruinese as well as Erkynlandish.A diverse Gardenborn people who call themselves Vao and are also known as Ocean Children or Changelings. They include many races, among them Dwarrow, Niskies, Hunën, Chikri, Ghants, Kilpa, the Hidden, and Cary Men. Historically servants and slaves of the Keida'ya, they came from the Garden to Osten Ard and built all of the Nine Sithi cities. Though denied the near-immortality of the Sithi and Norns, they are very long-lived and unusually adaptable, taking on traits shaped by the places and peoples among whom they live. Notable Tinukeda'ya include Gan Itai, Valada Geloë, Ruyan Vé, Yis-fidri, and Yis-hadra.An Erkynlander jester in long service to Prester John and attached to Josua's company. His true name is Cruinh, but he took the name Towser after a jest involving one of King John's hounds. Elderly, bald, wrinkled, bent in posture and legs, fond of wine, and often dreary beneath his silliness, he plays lute, sings sweetly, and has a deep store of songs and verse. Despite age and forgetfulness, he preserves important memories of John, Camaris, Bright-Nail, Thorn, and the old days of the realm.One of the Sithi Nine Cities, initially the first city and greatest of the Sithi cities before snow and ice overtook it. It was noted for sunrise vistas and tall towers visible from miles away when painted red by the dawn.A dragon mountain north of the White Waste, called Yijarjuk in Qanuc. It is associated with the great white dragon Igjarjuk and with journeys into the dangerous northern highlands.An earldom in northwestern Erkynland on the east bank of the Greenwade, described as the westernmost tip of Erkynland. During the Storm King's War it is ruled by Earl Guthwulf.Queen of the Norns of Stormspike and mistress of Nakkiga, wife of the late Ekimeniso Blackstaff and mother of Drukhi. The oldest living creature born in the Garden, she is at least ten thousand years old and the central figure of Hikeda'ya reverence. Once beautiful, now very thin with prominent bones and paper-white skin, she wears a famous silver mask. Spiteful, cruel, manipulative, and shaped by ancient mourning, she rules a society that treats obedience to her as sacred duty. Her people call her Mother of All and organize much of their law, ritual, and service around her will.A blunt-spoken wise woman of the Aldheorte with a reputation as a witch, calling herself Protectress of the Forest. Likely Tinukeda'ya, she lives in a lonely lake-house that seems to Simon to have giant clawed feet beneath it. Not very tall, broad-faced, sun-browned, with short hair once black and now grey-shot, a sharp downward-curving nose, heavy-lidded yellow eyes, and a posture of strength, she is wise, terse, and formidable. She communes with nature, walks the dream-road, knows the League of the Scroll, and can use aspects of the Art including owl-shape, bird-speech, wind-summoning, and dream travel.A Nabbanai nobleman of the Benidrivine bloodline, youngest son of Leobardis and Nessalanta, brother of Benigaris and Antippa, and cousin of Miriamele through Hylissa. Handsome, tall, thin, pale, watery-eyed, timid, stubborn, honorable, and apologetic in posture, he is more naturally suited to priesthood than war. Mocked for priestly inclinations, he turns toward a military career largely to impress his father, despite being ill-suited to it. He carries the Warmaster's baton of the Benidrivine house.A Nabbanai Aedonite priest who rises from Escritor to Lector after Ranessin. Very large and fat, with a round head, he is politic, deferential, cunning in a cautious way, and able to talk at length while saying little. He places himself near whoever seems likely to prevail, aware of political mutterings around Elias and Leobardis but rarely useful to those seeking decisive action. He often carries a box of sweets and is moved by an eight-man litter.The ancestral home of the Gardenborn across the Dreaming Sea, also called the Garden that is Vanished, the Lost Garden, or simply the Garden. It is remembered as a place of mountains, valleys, wild witchwood groves, the living Dreaming Sea, and origins shared by the Sithi, Norns, and Tinukeda'ya.Tiamak's native village in the Wran. It is one of the named settlements of the Wrannamen, tied to marsh life, boats, stilted dwellings, and the customs of Tiamak's people.An island in the Bay of Firannos, birthplace of Camaris and the Benidrivine House. Its notable features include a harbor and docks.A Norn lord and High Magister of the Order of Builders, full name Viyeki set-Enduya. White-haired, alabaster-skinned, black-eyed, with defined cheeks and jaw, he is a skilled engineer descended from Enduyo of Kementari. Son of the justiciar and admired court artist Urayeki, he remembers the reaction in Nakkiga to the fall of Asu'a. He marries Khimabu and becomes close to Yaarike, head of the Builders, who takes him under his wing. His family includes his daughter Nezeru and Tzoja, his favored mortal concubine.A Thrithings-woman of Clan Mehrdon, daughter of Fikolmij and sister of Hyara, and companion of Prince Josua. Tall, slender, dark-eyed, ivory-skinned, with raven-black curly hair and a hawklike nose, she values elegance and works hard to assert her place as lady of Naglimund despite prejudice from others. Willful, intelligent, quick-tempered, and shaped by a culture where women have little formal power, she left her clan to follow Josua. She often clashes with him, but is driven by love, pride, and a fierce desire for women to have a voice in decisions that shape the world.An island off the coast of Erkynland and the birthplace of Prester John. Its place in the geography of Osten Ard is tied to the High King's origins.A castle fortress of rock on a hilltop at the southern mouth of the Gleniwent, opposite Meremund. It is described as "nothing but a hill and a harbor flame," suggesting a fortress-like settlement rather than a conventional city.A marshy region forming the eastern coast of the Bay of Firannos and inhabited by the Wrannamen. It is a vast tangle of watercourses, mangroves, sandbars, trees, grasses, tropical storms, crocodiles, ghants, birds, water beetles, snakes, crabs, fish, and tree-dwelling animals.The inhabitants of the Wran, a short, brown-skinned human people living in tribal villages amid marsh and watercourse. Wrannamen families are large, often with several generations in one or two stilted huts. They travel by boat or stilt, wear breechclouts and robes in the hot climate, trap crabs and swamp creatures, fish, forage yellowroot and fern, brew fern beer, and bake flat breads on hot stones. Their houses are built on stilts with bark roofs, and clay potters make bowls for food and drink. Their villages are governed by elders, and tribal duty weighs heavily.A Perdruinese innkeeper, former Aedonite nun, Scrollbearer, and proprietress of Pelippa's Bowl in Kwanitupul. Fiercely clever, sharp-eyed, devout, and scholarly, she left her order while remaining religious. She befriended Morgenes and joined the League of the Scroll, putting forward Dinivan and Pryrates as candidates when the League sought seven members. Pelippa's Bowl passes from her household to her niece Charystra.The mountainous homeland of the Qanuc. It is associated with the Trollfells, Qanuc villages such as Mintahoq, and the high northern culture of the people humans often call trolls.A Dwarrow of the Tinukeda'ya and keeper of Pattern Hall, married to Yis-hadra. He belongs to the Dwarrow branch of the Vao, the people associated with hidden halls, stonework, metalwork, and Mezutu'a.A Dwarrow of the Tinukeda'ya and keeper of Pattern Hall, married to Yis-fidri. She belongs to the Dwarrow branch of the Vao, the people associated with hidden halls, stonework, metalwork, and Mezutu'a.